values:
For some reason other the past few days I've had sudden surge in wanting to listen to all my gothic music again. It started with Paradise Lost's Draconian Times as I was returning to univeristy on Monday. By the evening I was in the throes of The Gathering and Opeth and now I find myself listening to large amounts of My Dying Bride.

I just felt the need to vent that.

In case I forget to say it tomorrow: Merry Christmas to all of you, be you Old VtM Forum-ers, fellow Gamers, Old Friends, New Friends or Dogs (Gus).

Have a Great Time.

Actual contact has been made with Harry "It Didn't Go to Plan" Richardson. 

This afternoon I recieved an email from him, which resulted in his visting my home. He lives! Despite having had his internet cut off, due to accusations of piracy, and being terrified of his inbox due to F***book emails, he lives.

I have done my best to show him how to salvage his inbox through the magic of Gmail and filters. He has joined the Piledrivers and Powerbombs game that I'm attempting to run via email and we can only hope this will go well. I may actually use LJ as a place to store session infomation - this remains to be seen. Soon I shall make him watch The Gamers and I believe I have his permission to use his old PCs as NPCs in a game I may soon run.

I thought I'd share the good news!

As Vampir (who I would link to if I remembered how) commented, complained, and mourned the fact that I'm no longer posting on LJ I thought I'd attempt to struggle back into the habit of posting. The bane of course is when I run out of things to say, which always happens, but for now I have Dragonmeet 2008 as fuel.

It's late now, so a proper post on all of that will follow. Being at university (UCL, London) means that I may have more time to write LJ posts, even if I have a lot less *free* time on my hands. Studying history means I have to read like crazy, which cuts down on the time for myself, but the amount of staff contact is pretty low.

Of course I'm still a gamer a heart. Although I sadly no longer have companions to play VTES with, I have joined the UCL Roleplaying Society and am running two games of my own outside of it, which you shall all hear about soon enough.

Here's to keeping in touch with the internet group...

Me? Introverted? Never! Well, surely I'm a bit warmer then claimed!

I Am A: Lawful Good Elf Wizard (1st Level)

Ability Scores:
Strength-12
Dexterity-9
Constitution-15
Intelligence-15
Wisdom-13
Charisma-14

Alignment:
Lawful Good A lawful good character acts as a good person is expected or required to act. He combines a commitment to oppose evil with the discipline to fight relentlessly. He tells the truth, keeps his word, helps those in need, and speaks out against injustice. A lawful good character hates to see the guilty go unpunished. Lawful good is the best alignment you can be because it combines honor and compassion. However, lawful good can be a dangerous alignment because it restricts freedom and criminalizes self-interest.

Race:
Elves are known for their poetry, song, and magical arts, but when danger threatens they show great skill with weapons and strategy. Elves can live to be over 700 years old and, by human standards, are slow to make friends and enemies, and even slower to forget them. Elves are slim and stand 4.5 to 5.5 feet tall. They have no facial or body hair, prefer comfortable clothes, and possess unearthly grace. Many others races find them hauntingly beautiful.

Class:
Wizards are arcane spellcasters who depend on intensive study to create their magic. To wizards, magic is not a talent but a difficult, rewarding art. When they are prepared for battle, wizards can use their spells to devastating effect. When caught by surprise, they are vulnerable. The wizard's strength is her spells, everything else is secondary. She learns new spells as she experiments and grows in experience, and she can also learn them from other wizards. In addition, over time a wizard learns to manipulate her spells so they go farther, work better, or are improved in some other way. A wizard can call a familiar- a small, magical, animal companion that serves her. With a high Intelligence, wizards are capable of casting very high levels of spells.

Find out What Kind of Dungeons and Dragons Character Would You Be?, courtesy of Easydamus (e-mail)

Can't say I expected to be lawful good or a wizard, but there you go!

Was great fun. I'll say more when I'm not about to go to bed.

Update: This was a lovely evening. The Islington Carling Academy is only a 15 minute or so bus ride away from my house so Lysi and were able to get there very early - before the doors had even opened. We got inside pretty quickly and made our way to the front. The venue took awhile to fill up, but fill up it did!

The support band Novembre got a rather lackluster reception. I'm not really that familiar with them, but they didn't play any of their softer stuff that I do know, so it was basically a quick setlist during which the vocalist screamed at us. The drummer however was very impressive; he worked bloody hard and looked like he wanted to die. The bassist looked like a well groomed hobo who was just delighted to be on stage. At one point (when the bassist was indulging in a solo) the vocalist shouted mockingly:

"Look at the bass!"

Suck it dry Jem Jem.

Once Paradise Lost come out the room exploded into a mosh pit, which calmed down enough for the mosher to find their own pit, while Lysi and I kept our spot in front of Greg (the guitarist). The band was in excellent humour throughout the evening and there was plenty of interaction with the crowd. The setlist was supurb and everything translated excellently live. While I might have made some additions (more Draconian Times tracks) I wouldn't have removed anything.

Now to wait for them to come back at some point!

Setlist:

The Enemy
Ash and Debris
Grey
No Celebration
So Much Is Lost
As I Die

I'm pretty sure that's my arm on the left at the opening, striking in time with the drums, you can tell by my watch. So the bouncing blond head towards the left would be the back of Lysi's head. That might even be my face at 0:43-0:44

It's been a long time since I least posted an entry. What can I say, between universities, history reading, running my Star Wars game *and* school and sleep it's been hard to find time to say anything about what I've been doing!

Still some things certainly deserve a mention. Firstly, it's December now, which is wonderful since I love Christmas so much. The downside of that is that I've yet to manage to really think about what I want for Christmas, or what I should get for other people. It looks like some rushed shopping is in order pretty soon! Personally I'd wanted a copy of Rock Band for Christmas, but since it's not released in the EU yet, that's not going to happen. *Sigh*

December also means Dragonmeet and my, a good time was had this year! Our party was significantly larger than it had been in 2006, Jem Jem, Harry, Krys and I were joined by Thomas and John (Of Jar-Head White Wolf forums game). John turned out to be a lovely, friendly individual as expected, and not some insane rapist as one often fears. We all managed to find each other at Victoria without too much difficulty in the morning, though Jem Jem was running late (So, on time for him). John actually walked past Harry and I and the three of us had that amusing moment when you *think* you've recognised someone you've never seen, but you're worried that you might terrify a total stranger.

Soon enough we were united as a unit and went in search of Kensington, Unfortunately the line to get tickets for the tube at Victoria station were insane, so at my suggestion we took the bus instead. Under Harry's leadership and geographical skills (vastly superior to mine) we managed to arrive at Kensington High Street having spent a lengthy bus journey chatting about White Wolf games, the horror of the London Lite paper and the fact that John was spending his time popping "Pro-Plus" pills, having only got 3 hours of sleep the previous night.

During this time I received a call from Jem Jem who had managed to arrive at our destination before the rest of us. (Oh, the shame!). He and I had difficulty communicating, all I really gathered was that he was low on, or had no credit and that there was something Norwegian.

You can imagine my confusion.

We assumed that he meant he'd meet us near some form of Norwegian shop. When we failed to find one (having also checked inside the station) Harry suggested that perhaps he'd said Con-Ven-Shon rather than Nor-Wee-Gen. This made sense to us all so we trotted off to the venue. After receiving goody bags, packed full of, well, goodies (including a promotional D6) we got inside and took a look around.

No Jem Jem.

We realised we couldn't call him as his phone seemed to be off. I decided to try again, whereupon he found us all as we shopped. It turns out he'd borrowed a Norwegian woman's phone and had stayed at the station, yet we'd managed to somehow miss him when we went there.

We spend a lot of time dashing around grabbing free stuff (13 Clone Troopers, 3 Tie Interceptors, 60+ dice among other things for me) before going out for lunch. By the time we'd returned a number of the games no longer had enough spaces for six people, but we were resolved to play as a group. Having to abandon Scion and other games we grabbed all the spaces for the Warhammer Fantasy RPG.

 The game turned out to be good fun. Jem Jem was a clumsy in game as he is in real life. John was well organised and helped us work as a unit, even if he tried to throw a knife having only one eye. Krys was our quiet sergeant, leading us, the noble town watch and I was reforming ex-druggie who spent most of the game trying to secure some drugs.

I succeeded there, diverting certain supplies we confiscated from the evidence room to my own pocket.

The guard ended up spending a lot of time complaining about foreigners, Halflings, journalists, students and goblin excrement. As John noted, we spent more time attacking and threatening students, arresting harmless drug dealers (the dealer himself got dog piled by three of us and still took an eon to club into unconsciousness) than tracking down Goblins and serial killers.

We know where our priorities lie!

All in all, the day was delightful. Krys was too kind and got me a Christmas present (a huge Star Wars minis booster pack, a massive add to my Star Wars RPG), for which I can only thank him profusely. John turned out to be excellent company a great guy to game with, as could only have been expected. Man hugs were exchanged at the end and hopefully we'll all see each other again sooner rather than later.

My Stars Wars game continues to go well.

I have my Cambridge interview tomorrow...Fingers crossed! Paradise Lost live on Wednesday will hopefully take the edge off of that mind.

Raw was great fun. Although live it lost some of the excitment in that the music wasn't as clear and you didn't have JR and King commentating, the moves themselves and the general "sport" gained a lot from being live. It really struck home how large and powerful a lot of the WWE Superstars are.

The matches were as follows:

Carlito Vs William Regal

Not bad at all. Carlito's cool on the mike and came out talking trash about England, English women (they're ugly) and English men (who've yet to work out that tight jeans are for women. I suspect this was aimed at Harry). He declared he wanted to fight and Englishman, whereupon Regal come out and the two had a match, won by Regal. Good fun, but nothing vastly exciting.

Super Crazy Vs. Snitsky

We were surprised, and quite thrilled, to see Super Crazy, but our hearts sank when we realised he was doomed to job to Snitsky (who looks HUGE live). Super Crazy showed off his athletic prowess, while Snitsky displayed his raw power. A impressive moment was when Snitsky kicked out of Super Crazy's pin and in the process, hurled Super Crazy over a visibly surprised and panicked Referee.

Hardcore Holly and Cody Rhodes Vs. Lance Cade and Trevor Murdock (Word Tag Team Titles)

As might have been expected, Cade and Murdock retained, but this was a lively exciting match with plenty of power from the champions and athleticism from Cody. Quite exciting.

Val Venis Vs. Mr Kennedy

Kennedy showed off his mike skills, which was good fun, though at first he refused to finish his catchphrase (being heel), though he relented after he won. Fun enough, but it dragged on a bit.

Harry Smith Vs. Santino Marrella

Nobody knew who Harry Smith was until he mentioned he was the son of the British Bulldog. He and Marella showed off some quite neat moves, being small men, with Smith picking up the victory. Afterwards Hacksaw Jim Duggen came out with the Union Jack and had every chant out "England", rather than "USA" for once.

Candice Michelle Vs. Beth Phoenix (Women's Title)

As this came after the intermisson we all sighed, expecting a pretty poor escuse for softcore porn. How wrong we where, Candice has massivly improved since I las tpaied any attention to her and Beth Phoneix is STRONG. One of the best matches of the night and a real surprise. Very good. Beth retained, of course

Tripple H Vs. Umaga (Street Fight)

We all assumed that this was the main event and were thus suprised and a little upset that we didn't get to see Jeff Hardy or Randy Orton. The place was on fire when Tripple H's music hit and he came out. The match itself was nice and brutal, though we didn't get the tables we were chanting for. Tripple H picked up the win and Umaga could hardly get up afterwards. A Crowd pleaser.

Jeff Hardy Vs. Randy Orton (WWE title)

We were suprised to see Jeff in the main event for the title and thus knew there was no way he would win. Despite that he got a rock star reception and the crowd was exciting by a high flying match that ended with a thunderous RKO. When Randy came in Jonathan, Harry and I were all pulling Randy's pose and Harry and I are pretty sure that Randy spotted us, since he paused for a brief moment.

All in all a great evening. Our seats were much better than expected, as they were in the aisle and thus not blocked by anyone and as we were at the back we could stand when we wanted to. The only down side of thee vening ws getting back quite late and having to share a train on the way with "Captin Stinky" a man who smelt more horrible than anything I've smelled in months, like a combination of old tobbaco and gone off Guinness. Disgusting!

Last weekend John (my step-father) took me up to go and watch the Australia Vs. England match in a bar before going on to watch some live rugby (Harlequins Vs. Bristol). A good day was had, combining rugby and plenty of Guinness. So, obviously I watched tonight's match.

Up until those last 5 minutes my gut was sinking, but all of a sudden, bang, a few Sweet Chin Music worthy superkicks and England had a place in the World Cup final!

Anyway, what else is new? Not much really. Jem Jem and I had a brief falling out, most of which was due to miscommunication and a lack of tact on my part, but, credit to him, he gave me a chance to explain myself and all is well. Props to him.

Other than that there really isn't much else. I'll be heading out to see Paradise Lost on December 4th having located someone to accompany me (Lysi) and am now making sure I have a firm grip on all eleven (!) of their albums. Despite Douglas' claims I ought to have gotten bored of listening to moslty them over the past two weeks, eleven albums is enough to keep me fresh.

Harry, Lysi and I will be going to see Nightwish in March, but next Tuesday Harry, Jonathan and I will all be of to see RAW at Wembley Arena. It's just such a shame Cena was injured just a few weeks ago, now we shan't get to see him.

I and five of my lucky friends will be seeing KoRn in concert in January. Douglas will loose his mosh pit virginity.

This ought to be fun.

Today I gave myself a haircut.

With my own hair...

That is to say, I gave myself a papercut, with my own hair. This happen while I was fiddling with it.

I feel like such an idiot.

My brother has revealed himself as a disgustingly egocentric immature volatile individual, who, at this point in time, I no longer have any sympathy. Were it not for the fact that it would upset my mother, I would be delighted if he moved out of the house, or if he were to suffer a miserable transition to the junior sixth.

I'll probably say more about this once my head is more level. Suffice to say as of the past hour my home life has become very miserable.

In other, nicer news I'm back at school. My timetable looks fine and my new English teacher doesn't seem bad.

Yesterday Krys, Krys' sister, Jem Jem and I all got together on Oxford Street to spend the day together and to try to find some shoes for Krys' sister and perhaps some trousers for the man himself. Unfortunately it seems we were failed as regards these goals, but nevertheless a good time was had and I was proven correct in my assertion that there were plenty of places to get shoes there. After a little bit of hassle trying to find each other, involving me texting Krys from about 10 metres away, then promptly spotting him after having sent it, we realised that James was, as usual, running about an hour late. So we gave upon him and did some browsing until he eventually turned up, whereupon we continued our browsing; popping into various shoe shops and other sports shops. While the Poles tried various things on Jem Jem and I looked at the tasteless slogans across the various T-Shirts and played around with what was on display: After that a quick trip to Metal Militia was in order, for some mocking and quick browsing, resulting in me obtaining a Korn poster, which I delighting in using as a cane for Jem Jem's head and a lecture stick for pointing at things. Krys picked up a few badges, and after some fumbling around on the streets we ended up Gosh Comics and finally playing games where Krys picked up Scion and we had a lovely chat with the nice man behind the counter about his VAST (and I mean VAST) Cthulhu Hereoclix model. It was so big they couldn't have it in the shelf with its wings attached. Trying to get lunch was slightly difficult as Jem Jem was making a fuss about everything and I had my dentists appointment shortly, which meant I was forced to rush my meal and then (sadly) leave everyone and run for the tube. A tube journey followed and then I got stressed as I had to wait for a bus, which, as luck would have it, was also carrying my father. Unfortunately when we arrived at the dentist to meet my brother we were told that the bastard had cancelled our appointment' therefore wasting my time. Anyway; here are a few pictures from the day:

I've just heard that Lacuna Coil's song Closer (from Karmacode) will be a song featured on Guitar Hero 3. Even better, it'll be master track, which means no lousy covers. Since Lacuna Coil are one of the bands I'm very fond of, and never thought would make it into such a game (since they're not some huge metal band from the 80s) that's probably reason enough for me to buy Guitar Hero 3. Other than that though the only track on GH3 that really leaps out at me right now is Black Magic Woman by Santana, which is Santana and is thus awesome, though that's a cover version.

On the other hand Rock Band has master track copies of In Bloom (Nirvana) and Should I Stay Or Should I Go (The Clash), which are also awesome. Well, less so the Nirvana, but I'm a fan of The Clash and a passing fan of old Cobain.

Looks like I might have to consider both games...Sigh.

Now all I need is to see some Korn confirmed and I'll be a happy little boy.
Summer Slam is tonight and I'm already really tired. Nonetheless, Jem Jem and I are going to have to try to stay up for it. I may have to develop a taste for coffee...

Well, I got my results. 4 A's with my highest overall mark being 95% in history, though given the weird system they use I'm not 100% sure of my calculations.

Unfortunately my good friend Zain didn't get the 4 B's he needed to remain in the school. It is a sad day for us all.

Last night I fell down the main flight of stairs in my fathers house at about midnight. It was more or less pitch black as there were no lights on, so it took me awhile to work out what was actually happening. I remember wondering if I was going to break my neck.

Thankfully I didn't and my glasses didn't shatter or anything, but I woke up this morning to find that my right foot is in agony. I'm hoping I haven't broken my foot or anything, but until the pain killers I've taken kick in there's no way I'll be able to walk back to my mother's house.

I'd like to point out that I hadn't consumed any alcohol, so this was purely an act of complete and utter clumsy stupidity.

I'm home!

It's 1:43 in the morning.

My eyes hurt...

I went out and bought Korn's new album about an hour ago, so I thought I'd scrawl down my first impressions:

1. Ok, so I already knew that album was "Untitled" and I'd already seen the album art, but I still can't get over the fact that the album hasn't even got a name. The art, though not bad from an objective point of view, seems to have little to do with the band or album from my perspective so these are points that count against the album. That said the actual packaging of the super-deluxe-mega-happy-fun-chocolate-edition is quite nice and the art on the collectors cards inside is *much* better.

2. The intro track is an introduction along the lines of Dead on Issues. It sounds like something out of The Nightmare Before Christmas, very good.

3. Everything else? Uh...So far it all just blurs into one electronic mess. I'm not really expecting anything to stand out at this point, but this is definitely the successor to See You On The Other Side. Which was expected but not desired.

I suspect this means one of two things. Either this is an album that I'll view alongside SYOTOS as a disappointment, or, somehow it'll really grow on me. That does tend to happen with some albums... Fingers crossed.

On Friday my family and I all went up to Norfolk for the marriage of two dear family friends (one of whom is John's ex-stepson). The whole affair was really quite lovely and very sweet. Quite fortunately we managed to coexist as a family and didn't have any real difficulty with my brother, or various other wedding guests who we've had a slightly troubled past with. It was quite nice to put my suit back on and there's something strangely nice about everyone getting dressed up the way they did. This marks the second wedding I've attended (that I can remember), the first being my own father's wedding.

On Tuesday I'm going away to Malta for a week, just like last year. I'm looking forward to it as it should be nice, quite and warm. My hope is that it'll let me make some good progress with all of my history reading as well as some time to think seriously about my personal statment, which I need to have finished and sent to my school along with my UCAS form shortly after results day. Not that I'm looking forward to results day...

As far as the history reading goes, the sheer volume of it is quite daunting, but I'm quite enjoyed my reading on Lord Palmerston and the Liberal Party. The reading on the Russian Revolution isn't quite so interesting on the grounds that I hardly know anything about it, but the more I do the more intriguing it is at least. Though by my early impressions I can't see why people ever seem to have nice words for Lenin; from a moral idealistic standpoint he doesn't seem much nicer than Stalin to me.

Over the past two months my brother has mostly been living at my fathers as he had a fight with our stepfather and decided to move out.

Tonight was to be the first time that we all ate again here at home as a family. My brother went to his room and refused to eat with the rest of us.

The whole thing is becoming very fustrating.

And at long last I'm on holiday! Sure, I'll have to do a lot of history related reading, write my personal statment and all of that horrible UCAS stuff, but at least I can sleep in every day from now on!

VTES and RPGs here I come!

Chris Benoit died in his home in Atlanta along with his wife and seven year old son on Monday. According to the media it is believed that he killed his wife and son and then committed suicide.

The thought disgusts me and I hope it's not true, though I suspect it is.

That aside however I think Chris Benoit may well have the most skilled wrestler I ever saw. Harry and I often commented when we watched wrestling that you'd never see a bad Benoit match. He was definitely one of my favourite wrestlers.

The whole affair seems horrible, especially because, if I recall correctly, he leaves two other children.

And now my freedom ends and I'm forced to return to school for another three weeks. I hope the teachers are at least kind enough to shut up about the exams until we get our results back in August. I suspect they'll try to get us to work seeing as we're supposed to start the A2 courses, but I doubt they'll find us all very cooperative.

For my part I'll probably get swamped by Oxbridge meetings and briefings. Which sucks because it takes forever and tends to be rather stressful and intimidating. Especially given I'm not sure I even *am* Oxbridge material. Sigh.

That aside I want to keep working on getting the school role-playing society up and running. Finger crossed.

On Friday we have the sponsored walk. I am seriously hoping that I manage to avoid walking a bunch of small children. I just want to walk with my friends and play loud music...

Also I think I shall steal this game from  since it looks so amusing:

"Open your music player and set it to shuffle- Write down the first line of lyrics from each of the first 25 songs that come up! Let people guess, and then underline or strike out songs as they are correctly identified!"

No idea how well this'll go, or if I even have enough friends who might recongnise what I'm listening to, but whatever!
I'll be skipping tracks that name themselves in the first line, instrumentals, skits and any opening spoken words. Here we go:

2. This weight is so unbearable, caving my lungs.
3. Father thank you for making me rightous and accepted through the blood of Jesus.

And with Latin gone I'm free from exams for awhile! The Latin went pretty well. At least, the set texts did. I don't think the unseen was so good.

Anyway, time to relax!

The history exam went pretty well. I don't think I could have asked for a better paper, so if I don't do well, I guess that's just my fault. Hopefully it went as well as I think.

Now I have the rest of today to revise my Latin and then after tomorrow I'll be free of exams for the awhile! Just one more to go...

In about two and a half hours I'll be sitting in the salle taking my History exam. I don't feel quite as good about this one as I'd like to, there are some questions I definately don't want to get asked and I do feel that the teaching style of Miss Bennett hasn't done me much good.

So naturally she would be teaching me the topic that makes up the majority of the course.

Oh well. Best hope for the best and get some last minute reision done.

Relaxation was had and nobody was ill this time. Most satisfying.

On the downside my ankh fell off its clasp and shattered on the kitchen floor. A bad omen perhaps?

Now I return to revison. I have lots of Latin and History to go over.

I think the English Literature exam went well. It's always hard to tell with an English exam though. Either way, there's no point worrying about it now. I've got a week or so from now to my next two exams (History and Latin) so that should be plenty of time to revise them properly.

Tomorrow I will be holding a gathering with a number of my friends, so at least I'll get a chance to relax!

I think the English Language exam went fine. The paper wasn't horrible or anything and although I felt like I didn't have as much to write for one of the questions as I'd have liked to I think I did fine.

Fingers crossed.

Next up is English Literature on Friday. This one I'm not feeling as good about as I'd like to as I'm not too fond of my set texts particularly Heart Of Darkness. Well, we shall have to see how it goes.

Tomorrow I'll sit my first AS exam, English Language. I feel pretty good about it, as I've done well throughout the year, but annoyingly it's one of those subjects where there's not a vast amount you can do to revise for it. Ack, I'll just spend the rest of this evening looking over my notes and hope for the best.

Things have been quite a mess this past few weeks. My stepfather lost his temper and attacked my brother at supper two weekends ago and thus my brother has been spending most of his time staying with our father. Obviously we're all very shaken up by this, which is making home life quite uncomfortable. Nobody really seems to know how this is going to end up. Not great.

Yesterday my mother and I bought a load of beer cheaply, so we have lots to drink in the house. That's actually the only point of interest I can think of. Besides revision it's been something of a quite past few days. At least when we went on study leave on Wednesday we all went out for lunch. That was nice.

Anyway, back to the revision. 15 hours from now and I'll be sitting the exam. *Gulp*.

I saw Spiderman 3 on Friday. In fact, I went on a date Leciester Square.

With my brother...

Jonathan's date had fallen sick but he'd already bought the tickets for the great big Odeon there, so he ended up taking me instead. Not so good for him, but great for me!

The film itself? I liked it. It was quite ambitious I thought, in that they were trying to cover a lot of storylines and had to tie it into the previous two films, but I think they managed to pull it off. There was a good deal of reinterpretation going on (Venom in this film looks and feels more like Carnage to be honest and the Sandman is quite different), but I felt it worked on the whole. Some scenes were a bit off, such as Harry and his butler (those who've seen the film will know what I mean) and Peter's self centered attitude in a few scenes but all in all it was very cool. Far far far superior to X3...God I hated that film.

However, when Peter's out of the symbiote costume (as in, in his civies) he has an emo fringe...Fucking emos.

What was pretty painful to think about was the fact that my grandfather on my mother's side has an open book gravestone, with an empty page that was intended for his wife.
